Creating a simple web app that mimics the style of a classic RPG like Baldur's Gate can be quite complex, but I can provide you with a basic structure that includes HTML, CSS, and JavaScript all in one file. This example will create a simple interface with a character selection and a basic combat system.

Here's a simple implementation:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Baldur's Gate Clone</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #2c3e50;
            color: #ecf0f1;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        #character-selection, #combat {
            margin: 20px auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ecf0f1;
            border-radius: 10px;
            background-color: #34495e;
            width: 300px;
        }
        button {
            background-color: #e74c3c;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            width: 100%;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #c0392b;
        }
        #combat-log {
            margin-top: 10px;
            height: 100px;
            overflow-y: auto;
            background-color: #ecf0f1;
            color: #2c3e50;
            padding: 5px;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Baldur's Gate Clone</h1>

<div id="character-selection">
    <h2>Select Your Character</h2>
    <button onclick="selectCharacter('Warrior')">Warrior</button>
    <button onclick="selectCharacter('Mage')">Mage</button>
    <button onclick="selectCharacter('Rogue')">Rogue</button>
</div>

<div id="combat" style="display: none;">
    <h2>Combat</h2>
    <p id="character-info"></p>
    <button onclick="attack()">Attack</button>
    <div id="combat-log"></div>
</div>

<script>
    let character = null;

    function selectCharacter(type) {
        character = {
            type: type,
            health: 100,
            attackPower: type === 'Warrior' ? 15 : type === 'Mage' ? 10 : 12
        };
        document.getElementById('character-info').innerText = `${type} selected! Health: ${character.health}`;
        document.getElementById('character-selection').style.display = 'none';
        document.getElementById('combat').style.display = 'block';
    }

    function attack() {
        if (character) {
            const damage = Math.floor(Math.random() * character.attackPower);
            character.health -= damage;
            const log = document.getElementById('combat-log');
            log.innerText += `You attacked and dealt ${damage} damage! Health left: ${character.health}\n`;
            if (character.health <= 0) {
                log.innerText += "You have been defeated!\n";
                document.querySelector('button[onclick="attack()"]').disabled = true;
            }
        }
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The HTML consists of a title, a character selection section, and a combat section that appears after a character is selected.
- **CSS Styles**: The CSS styles are embedded in the `<style>` tag, providing a dark theme reminiscent of classic RPGs.
- **JavaScript Functionality**: The JavaScript handles character selection and a simple combat mechanic where the player can attack and see the results in a log.

### How to Use:
1. Copy the code above into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `baldurs_gate_clone.html`).
3. Open the file in a web browser to play the simple RPG clone.

This is a very basic implementation and can be expanded with more features like enemy encounters, leveling up, and more complex combat mechanics.
